Baylie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Bailey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailey","meanings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":4,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":6,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":20,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":22,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":35,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":55,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Francis Baylie was born about 1565, in Framlingham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Balles, was 29 and his mother, Joan Spalding, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Balie. He died in 1620, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 56, and was buried in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1565–1620":"umbes 1565–1620","1563–Male":"1563–Surnud","1565–1620":"1565–1620","1565–Female":"1565–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1537–Male":"1537–Surnud","1541–Female":"1541–Surnud","1571":"1571","1681":"1681","1560":"1560","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","1563":"1563","about 1565":"umbes 1565","1 August 1585":"1. august 1585","1537":"1537","Framlingham, Suffolk, England":"Framlingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Parham, Sussex, England":"Parham, Sussex, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1565–1620":"noin 1565–1620","1563–Male":"1563–Kuollut","1565–1620":"1565–1620","1565–Female":"1565–Kuollut","1560–Female":"1560–Kuollut","1585–1681":"1585–1681","1537–Male":"1537–Kuollut","1541–Female":"1541–Kuollut","1571":"1571","1681":"1681","1560":"1560","1569":